I know this was one of the most awaited posts by moms of teens but such videos take so much time because of research and editing but finally I am here with Low Toxic Cleansers for Teens/young skin/sensitive skin. When I choose skincare, I avoid ingredients that may disrupt hormones, irritate the skin, or carry long-term health concerns. This includes:

EDCs (Endocrine-Disrupting Chemicals) like parabens and phthalates

PEGs (Polyethylene Glycols), which may carry harmful impurities

Synthetic fragrance (often listed as “Fragrance” or “Parfum”)

Sulfates like SLS/SLES, which can strip and irritate skin

Phenoxyethanol in high concentrations (I'm okay with this if used under 1% as it's a safer preservative than parabens )
Comment "List" and I will send the BEGINNERS'S INGREDIENT LIST, if your account is private ,then pls DM me. 
Why do I recommend Korean products most fof the time? 
Korean brands have  innovative formulations and above all have stricter ingredients regulations. FDA bans only ~11 ingredients vs. Korea/EU’s 1000+.

The first time I spoke about this, many couldn't digest this. I was the same before but after some serious health diagnosis, I did some digging. 

Your skin is permeable, and what you apply topically can be absorbed directly into your bloodstream.

That's right! Pores and hair follicles act like direct pathways. This is why transdermal patches (like nicotine or hormone patches) work , chemicals go straight into your circulation, bypassing digestive filters.

This process, called dermal absorption, means common beauty chemicals (like phthalates, parabens, synthetic fragrances) can easily enter your system. Once there, studies show they can act as endocrine disruptors, potentially interfering with your hormones, especially your thyroid.

IF doing your own reearch, type "dermal absorption of EDCs or specific chemical groups" and or "link between EDCs and thyroid health" on Google and articles like this will show up https://www.niehs.nih.gov/health/topics/agents/endocrine Do check my channel "More Non Toxic info" for some links I will share.

This is exactly why I'm so passionate about non-toxic beauty and living. Every choice we make about what we put on our bodies is just as important as what we put in them.

Is your sunscreen silently messing with your hormones?

You might want to check the label. 🧴

Many popular sunscreens contain ingredients linked to endocrine disruption,including thyroid issues, reproductive health problems, and even early puberty in children. A lot of non tox advocates suggest to go for physical/mineral sunscreen however I am not very strict or hard on that as long as the product does not contain the ingredients I am avoiding,I am cool with it. 
The three product I mentioned here are chemical sunscreens.
All three use modern chemical filters that are photostable and safer options, such as:

Ethylhexyl Triazone

Diethylamino Hydroxybenzoyl Hexyl Benzoate

Bis-Ethylhexyloxyphenol Methoxyphenyl Triazine (Tinosorb S)

Polysilicone-15

Terephthalylidene Dicamphor Sulfonic Acid (Mexoryl SX) which are considered safer chemical filters (broad-spectrum, stable, less irritating, and not known endocrine disruptors).

Here’s what to watch out for:

❌ Oxybenzone

❌ Parabens (e.g., methylparaben, butylparaben)

❌ PEGs

❌ Fragrance / Parfum

❌ Phthalates

❌ Disodium EDTA

❌ Lake dyes

🧠 Why it matters:

Studies have found ingredients like oxybenzone can mimic estrogen and disrupt hormone levels. One NIH-backed study linked higher exposure to these chemicals with altered thyroid hormones in adults and pregnant women.

📚 Source: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1241915/
